<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><!--Transformation version 1.3--><legislativeDoc xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:noNamespaceSchemaLocation="http://www.lexisnexis.com/xmlschemas/content/public/legislativedoc/1/" schemaVersion="1.0"><legislativeDocHead><citations><citeForThisResource citeDefinition="#7159#349#000025#     1#          220#">Va. Code Ann. § 25.1-220</citeForThisResource></citations><legislativeBodyInfo><jurisdiction><jurisSystem normalizedLongName="Virginia" normalizedShortName="VA"/></jurisdiction></legislativeBodyInfo></legislativeDocHead><legislativeDocBody><statute><level levelType="section"><anchor id="_25.1-220"/><heading><desig>§ 25.1-220.</desig><title>Who determines issue of just compensation</title></heading><bodyText><p>The issue of just compensation shall be determined by a commission or a jury, upon a timely election made by an owner as provided in <citation type="statute" normalizedCite="VACODE 25.1-213"><content><span normalizedCite="Va. Code Ann. § 25.1-213">§ 25.1-213<locator><locatorKey><keyName name="citeReference"/><keyValue value="#7159#349#000025#     1#          213#"/></locatorKey></locator></span></content></citation>. However, by agreement of the petitioner and all the parties who are sui juris that have appeared or responded, or, if no owner upon proper notice has appeared or responded, or has filed an answer and grounds of defense that fails to elect to have the determination of just compensation made by either commissioners or a jury, then, upon motion of the petitioner, the issue of just compensation may be determined by the court.</p></bodyText><history><historyGroup groupType="history-citation"><historyItem><bodyText><p>1962, c. 426, § 25-46.19; 1984, c. 377; <citation normalizedCite="1991 VA CH 520"><content><span normalizedCite="1991 Va. Ch. 520">1991, c. 520<locator><locatorKey><keyName name="citeReference"/><keyValue value="#1834#131#1991#000520#"/></locatorKey></locator></span></content